title: Mickey Wall Hook
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Mickey Wall Hook

I didn't see any good Mickey wall hooks, and we are doing a Disney bathroom, so I designed a wall hook with a Mickey silhouette.

Printer:

XYZprinting da Vinci Pro 1.0

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm or lower

Infill:

30% or more for strength

Notes:

Recommended to print with ABS, PLA+/ToughPLA or PETG for strength. PLA may not work.

No supports, rafts, or brims needed. (There are 1-2 layers that are about 60 degrees from vertical so depending on your printer, a bit of sanding may be required on the top inside of the hook if it gets a little chunky like mine did.)

30% infill or more recommended for strength and durability.

I printed mine with PETG / 30% honeycomb infill and the hook feels like it can easily support 10-15lbs. You'll probably reach the drywall anchor limit before the hook actually breaks off.

Should fit most sizes of drywall anchor screws or wall bolts. A drywall anchor or stud mount is recommended so you don't rip a hole in your wall... who knows what your kids are gonna hang off this thing? :)
Recommended to finish with some type of glossy coating (resin, epoxy, varnish, etc), especially if you hang it up in a bathroom with a lot of moisture.

title: CR-10 RaspberryPi Ethernet Camera Mount Kit

description.text:
Warning: After using this for a bit myself, I'm going to go back to a standard pi camera and remote lights. The two IR LED's on each side have a metal disc on the back of them that gets really hot to the touch. Some recommend adding heat sinks to them. However these IR LED's are powered directly from the hardware of the board. You can NOT turn them off even using raspi-config or scripts. So I have elected to just not use them in this application.

See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2797774 for the standard RPi Camera.

I remixed a few other files and borrowed one file with no changes to create this RaspberryPi Mounting kit using a Vilros Raspberry Pi case to mount a Raspberry Pi Camera to a ball joint that plugs into the Ethernet port to position the camera cleaning. This all bolts to the side of the CR-10 control box using the factory screws and places the camera for OctoPrint at a nice angle. I know some prefer to mount directly to the buildplate, but I didn't want to add the mass or deal with cable management. I do need to replace my really long USB cable with a nice compact one to clean up the install a bit more.

For better control over the web camera in OctoPrint. Try using "System Command Editor" Plug-in and creating two new menu actions that use:
"sudo service webcamd start" to Turn Camera ON
and
"sudo service webcamd stop" to Turn Camera OFF.

title: 12 connector (10x 20AWG + 2x 16AWG) in-line wire plug
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Current Status: Work In Progress

This plug set was created out of a need for a quick, compact way to remove the hotend without using spade connectors (no commercially-available plug fit the size and pin density requirements). This plug was designed for use at the effector-end of the whip (frame-end plug coming soonish). Two inner holes for 18-16AWG heater wires, 10 outer holes for 20-24AWG fan/sensor/extruder wires. Uses Molex pins for all connections: .062" pin sets for outer connectors, .093" pin sets for inner connectors (commonly available at any decent electronics supplier).

Wing notches added to female plug. Final revision unless I notice a glaring error.

Note: Read print settings carefully - the settings listed are required for the plug to print properly with no hole breach.

Printer:

Ultibots D300VS

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.35mm or less extrusion width REQUIRED

Infill:

Any

Notes:

Layer thickness works best between .1mm-.2mm, but can be thicker if desired with minor deformation.

Extrusion width MUST be .35mm or less, so a .4mm or smaller nozzle is REQUIRED. If extrusion width is any larger, the slicer will fail to close the space between holes at the bottom of each plug, leading to gaps. Some slicers can be forced to fill those gaps with extrusion width greater than .35mm, but this will cause the holes to become much smaller and deform into irregular shapes.

Suggested filament is ABS/ASA or Nylon (any grade). I have not noticed any heat issues at the junction, but for safety's sake a plastic with high deformation and melting temps is preferred. If the plug does heat up, PLA will deform, allowing pins to back out and short across each other.

Acetone smoothing is not recommended at this time. The smoothing will flatten the ridges that the female pins use to stay secure (tab notch is coming in later revision), as well as deform/melt the thin walls between pins. Additionally, the ridges do help keep the plugs connected under stress.

Push male pins all the way through the plug until the locking tabs rest on the plug face (there are pockets designed into the plug face to keep all pins the same length). Push the female pins into the plug until they are flush with the plug face - the tabs will bite into the layer ridges inside the holes.

title: COLLENCE MOSFET Case with 70mm fan pattern

description.text:
This is a MOSFET case that I designed to fit a 70mm fan I had lying around, and this MOSFET I purchased from Amazon. I am a HUGE fan of all metal threads for durability, so all of the fastener connections are designed for thermal inserts. The 70mm fan also has threaded inserts, but they do not require heat, they just slip into the fan mounting holes (as shown in the preview images). Here is a bill of materials for size and quantity of the hardware I used in my project.

Hardware:
8x - M2.5 x 0.45 - 5mm SHCS

8x - M2.5 x 0.45 - 3.4mm thermal set inserts

4x - M2.5 Flat Washer

4x - M3 x 0.5 - 14mm SHCS

4x - M3 Flat Washer

4x - M3 x 0.5 Thread Insert

All M3 hardware is used to mount the fan, all M2.5 hardware is used to mount the MOSFET and fasten case halves together. See images for details.

Also, the the half circle lugs on either end of the case bottom are used to zip-tie the wires for strain relief. This way, the wires won't fatigue and break at the terminals.

If there is any interest, I can upload either STEP or Parasolid files if anyone wants to modify these parts to exclude the thermal inserts.

Printer:

Tronxy X3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

25%

Notes:

Supports are only suggest for the bottom part that the MOSFET mounts to, to help support the countersunk screw holes. Supports are not required for the top cover.

Installing thermal inserts

I used a soldering Iron to install the inserts into the top and bottom parts (~500-700F), as shown in the included images. They should be set flush or slightly countersunk. I used the soldering iron to heat them up and push them in half way. Then, I removed the soldering iron and used a flat piece of metal to push them flush with the rest of the mating surface. This way, they stay parallel to mounting surface and will align with the mating screws better. The trick is to go slow. Even after the soldering iron is removed, you'll have time to push them flush before they cool to the point that they are set.

Also, if you need to remove the inserts for any reason, simply install a screw into the insert and use a soldering iron to heat the screw head. Once the heat has transferred to the insert, it will become loose. Used pliers to pull the screw and the insert will come with it.

It is a little extra work and cost to use thermal inserts, but if you need to remove fasteners with any sort of frequency, you'll fall in love with them just like I have!

description.text: This is a quick test of what programs you can use to 3D print. In this case Google SketchUp was used.

This is a Ripple Cookie Cutter. It is for shaping cookie dough (or any other substance for that matter - be creative) into the Ripple Logo.

I recommend using PLA for any food touching object or children's toy, since most of the other materials are poisonous or at least not completely safe.

Print it with the top faced to the building plate.

If u have recommendations of any kind to make this a better design please don't hesitate to contact me.

Step 1

Let the cookie cutter cool down before you peel it from your printing bed.

Step 2

Look for little material artifacts and cut them off carefully

Step 3

Wash the cookie cutter carefully under warm (not hot) water

Step 4

Cut your cookie dough

Step 5

Wash the cookie cutter under warm water (It might deform in the dishwasher since PLA gets soft at around 65 °C)

Step 6

Enjoy your cookies :-)
It s branded with the name of my channel. If you want it removed or changed to a different slogan or name so you could use it as a gift for example, feel free to message me

Ripple is a real-time gross settlement system (RTGS), currency exchange and remittance network created by the Ripple company. Also called the Ripple Transaction Protocol (RTXP) or Ripple protocol, it is built upon a distributed open source Internet protocol, consensus ledger and native cryptocurrency called XRP (ripples). Released in 2012, Ripple purports to enable "secure, instantly and nearly free global financial transactions of any size with no chargebacks." It supports tokens representing fiat currency, cryptocurrency, commodity or any other unit of value such as frequent flier miles or mobile minutes. At its core, Ripple is based around a shared, public database or ledger, which uses a consensus process that allows for payments, exchanges and remittance in a distributed process.
[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ripple_(payment_protocol)]

Hello, here is my first big build with the Multi Profil System.
I have build an Case for my Printer.

Somebody will thing that is stupid and cost a lot of money.
I thing he is right, look at the part-list for the Case and this is only the Filament and no plate, extra Nutstones and Screws for the housing.
The walls are old election poster.
No energy cost and no construction time....but......

With this i have gain a lot of experience in 3d construction and printer setup.

And after some printing and testing i thing it improve the printer and the printing result.

No cold spots on the heated printing bed and with this less adhesion problems.
Less problems with bending in the cooling.
Less dust problem.

Ready to printing time is shorter.
Bed heading time from 20 to 50 degree in less than 1:50 min.

Here some of the things you should now

Dont place your printer on a wooden board, it will bend from the bedhead in the printing process and have bad influence at the printed thing.

The best underground to place your printer is a sheetrock plate.
Under the sheetrock place a 5cm styrodur (polystyrene) plate.

Fazit: make a case for your printer.

If you have a problem or an improvement for this thing please let me now it.

Sorry for the Thing in this. Thingiverse will let only treads with an *.STL file go online.

Notes:

Printed 3 per run with brim at .1mm resolution. My gcode for both PLA and ABS prints are included.

Print the iso chips

Print sets of iso chips at .1 mm resolution.

Print top label.xcf

Open tap label.xcf in in the open source image editor, Gimp, and print on 8.5x11 paper (laser printing works best).

Add gloss layer to the top label

Use clear packing tape and cover the page of labels you just printed to give the labels a glossy look. Then use scissors or a paper cutter to cut it down to individual labels. Toss out any labels that have trapped dust or hair, show flaws, or the tape overlaps.

Finished top labels in the center. They will wrap around the iso chips on one side. Print the Tile xcf images on laser transparency film

There are three different circuit patterns (Tile1, Tile 2, Tile3) just to introduce some randomness into the look of the chips, so I print one of each. Use Laser transparency film from amazon. Cut these out, there is usually one row on the side that is incomplete or short, so toss that out. This usually takes some time. Using the paper cutter I usually have to tape down the sheets as I cut as the sheets like to warp and bend as I cut, which can ruin the cut. Taping the free sides down reduces this effect.

Glue on labels.

I use a plain white UHU glue stick, and thoroughly apply glue to the back of the top label. To do this I lay the labels face down on a piece of scrap paper and run the glue stick over them. (this works well for the circuit labels you'll do later as well).

Place the label on the chip, line up the label to be in the center of the top box, and with the right hand side. Wrap the label to the left, around the back, and back to the right. Some will stick out past the edge, you can cut this extra off with an exacto knife.

Add label by lining it up at the right hand side. Wrap it around the back. Cut off any extra that peeks out. Add circuit image

Add a fair amount of glue with the glue stick to the circuit label. Be sure to apply glue to the printed (non-glossy side). We want the glossy side to be the part that shows. The circuit label should fit nicely in the cutout in the isolinear chip. press it down so that the label is stuck in there firmly with the glue. Now you're done!

remixed_from.title: E3D V6 Mount with Modular Fan Ducts for Tevo Tarantula Modular X Carriage

title: Modular carriage with magnetic hotend mounts and bltouch support - Tevo Tarantula

description.text:
This is a remix of the Modular carriage by MSA and the E3D V6 Mount by Ahalekelly.

Lot of the files contained in this pack are directly coming from those things without modifications, I've just included them so it's easier for you.

Please check these original things before using mine to make sure you understand how to use and what you need to install those upgrades.

Modular carriage :

  • Replaced the hotend screw holes from the original Modular carriage by MSA by 3mm x 6mm magnets housings
  • Added an alternative xc_p3 part to be able to glue leds on an angle
  • Included the endstop bracket by Ahalekelly

Hotend mounts :

  • Modified the E3D V6 Mount by Ahalekelly to use magnets instead of screws
  • Separated the fan parts so only the hotend is swapped, the fans stays attached to the carriage
  • Added a support for the BLTouch sensor on the right fan
  • Added a stock hotend mount following the same principle than the E3D one

This works perfectly on my printer, let me know if you have any issue with this pack.

comments.text:
So I’m thinking about pulling he trigger on making this
but before I commit and buy the magents, can someone explain the purpose of the magnets? I see them visible so not all of them are making contact with other magents? If the hotend gets bumped will it skew?
comments.author: timothywaldvogel

comments.text:
There are magnets on the carriage and on the hotend mounts.
They are visible on the mounts because they don't make direct contact with the ones on the carriage, there is .8mm (if I remember correctly) of plastic between the magnets but they are strong enough to keep the mounts in place.
I did that to make sure no magnet get out of it's housing and stay stuck against an other magnet.
To avoid the mounts to skew if there is a bump, I made two small slots on top and bottom of the mounts that match the carriage so that the mounts are stuck in place vertically.
I hope I've explained that clearly :)

description.text: This is a slightly edited version of AccurateLaserEngraving's source; I did some cleanup on the design file and made it into a rounded rectangle instead.

Introduction

I had some trouble getting a clean SVG from the source design; finally I was able to convert the CorelDraw file. I then edited the paths a bit in Inkscape to ensure that the numbers didn't have lines underneath.

I added corner holes thinking that I might want to stack two pieces to make an enclosure for the card deck and pegs as well.

Preparation

I first stuck a piece of self-adhesive walnut veneer (keeping the masking paper on the top) to a piece of 1/4" cast clear acrylic, then measured the resultant thickness.

Cutting

I uploaded the SVG to my Glowforge laser cutter, entered the actual thickness of the piece, changed the numbers to an engrave, the paths to scores, and the holes and outside cut to cuts. I then told it that I was using walnut veneer and wrote down the manual settings for the engrave and the score. Then I changed the material type to 1/4" acrylic and wrote down the numbers for the cut. The order of the steps was this:

  • numbers (engrave on veneer)
  • track lines (score on veneer)
  • holes (cut through acrylic)
  • outer border (cut through acrylic)

The cuts could have stood to be a little bit slower, but not much.

Post-processing

I then ran the laser, peeled the masking paper (weeding with Gorilla Tape as required), and pushed through the holes that didn't fall out using a small screwdriver.

description.text:
Note: This puzzle DOES NOT require screws or springs.

I 3D printed this 3x3 Puzzle (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2746941), but I found it extremely hard to assemble the center pieces to the core without snapping them in two. I integrated this cube with the plug from this plus-cube puzzle (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1293292), and it worked perfectly.

Sorry for my terrible photo quality (camera was a $40 Gopro knock-off from Amazon).

Part Details:
Print 1 core, 6 centers, 6 plugs, 8 corners, and 12 edges. The corners and edges will need support, but the centers, plugs, and core should print fine without.

3x3_Plug_Tight.stl and 3x3_Plug_Loose.stl - these are the same thing, but Plug_Tight is slightly shorter for a tighter fit. If you want a looser cube, Print Plug_Loose, and vice-versa.

Printer:

BIBO 2 Touch

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

30

Notes:

Print with PLA. The only pieces that require support are the edges and corners. I used rafts for everything, but it is not required.

Remove as much support material as possible and sand down the inside of the pieces if you can; it helps the turning of the puzzle a lot. I can solve a normal speedcube sub-30, and my times for this 3D printed one is around 40-60 seconds. This is not bad if you take in account that this was 3D printed and does not need screws or springs.

Assemble all the centers and plugs into the core first. The plugs will wear down and pop out if you insert and un-insert them multiple times ( I have no reason why you would un-insert them though). After the first step, it is fairly straightforward until the final piece. Assemble the first and second layers, and the last layer until you have three final pieces to insert, two corners and an edge. Add in the two corners, and all that's remaining is the final edge. To insert this, you turn the top face a bit and pop it in with not much exerted force.

I used sharpies to color my cube, but it is difficult to distinguish red and orange sometimes. If you print this, I recommend stickers.

I hope you enjoy this! If you have any questions, leave a comment!

I designed and remixed some mounts. I was inspired by the phone mount in my truck, it uses these little slide mounts. I designed, re-designed, re-mixed, stole, borrowed, was inspired by, you get my point.

The mounts:
a stand alone mount
a gopro mount
2) 35mm din rail mounts, one centered and one lowered

There is a stand alone slide mount with 2 screw holes. You can mount this bracket anywhere. If you mount a box right to this bracket without using the gopro hinge, then you will need to countersink the screw holes and use flat head screws to mount the bracket. Or use 2 sided mirror tape.

The gopro slide mount has both parts on a common brim for easy printing. Trim away post print. I found that the original gopro mount was a little tight so I spaced out the hinge area a little bit. So far they fit well into every gopro mount I have tried, including the store bought ones.
Here is a short video: https://youtu.be/ge3tVdlT7Fg

I searched for “Bolt Nut Screws for Gopro” on Ebay and bought some long thumb screws. They work great with this mount. If you don't want to use the gopro screws then an 8-32 X 3/4 works just as well. You'll need a screwdriver though. Better for an unseen, permanent mount.

You can mount any of these boxes right to a din rail, or sandwich a gopro mount between them so you can aim your box up or down.

I redesigned the din rail clip so it’s stronger now, and fits a 35mm din rail a little better, and it is easier to snap on and off without breaking it.

There are 2 slide mount brackets that will bolt onto the din rail clip. One has a centered slide mount, the other one is slightly lower than center. This is for the larger boxes. I added 2 square holes in these mounts that line up with the square hole in the clip, so it doesn’t matter which way you install it, you will be able to slide a small screwdriver in there and pop the clip off the din rail.

The boxes and lids:
my original arduino boxes
my compact arduino boxes
my desk top meter box
my 1602 LCD box
my 2-8X8 LED box
my 4-8X8 LED box

My Arduino Boxes have a solid bottom. I redesigned the single bay box with an open bottom. I added a 0.50mm brim for bed adhesion. Trim away post print. Then I added a slide mount to the blank lid. Now you can mount my original arduino boxes with this slide mount gopro system

My Compact Arduino Boxes – I added the slide mount to a blank lid.

Desktop Meter Box – I chopped off the back to make it flat and added my slide mount

My 1602 LCD box – This was a total re-design. I made the box as small as I could, and still house the 1602. I added a nano rail in the lid, as well as my slide mount. There are a couple of "keepers" in the nano rail to hold it in place. You have to push past them when installing the nano.

My (2) 8X8 LED box and my (4) 8X8 LED box. I just added the slide mount to the bottom of the box. One slide mount on the 2 bay box, and 2 slide mounts on the 4 bay box. I also segmented the bottom of the 4 bay box, trying to minimize ABS warping

The file list:

2 8X8 bezel---the front bezel for the 2 bay 8X8 LED matrix box
2 8X8 bwsm---the 2 bay 8X8 LED matrix box with a slide mount
4 8X8 bezel---the front bezel for the 4 bay 8X8 LED matrix box

Print two of the legs!

Assembly

Place the screen face-down inside the bezel. Remember that the screen borders are not symmetrical - place the smaller border towards the top.

Place the retainer over top of the display and secure with 5 M3 6mm flathead screws (McMaster Carr part 91420A116) through the bezel sides and top.

Secure the legs to the back of the screen with 4 x M3 5mm screws (eg. McMaster Carr 90116A150).

When attaching the legs, do not use screws longer than 5mm without using washers and/or paying close attention to the depth of the screw as you can penetrate and destroy the display - you have been warned.

If you're using the Rasberry Pi case on the back of the display, the display adapter holds the lower half in place. Use the 12mm hex standoffs that come with the display to secure the display adapter over top of the case shell.

The lower half of the Raspi case is for Rasperry Pi 3, and the holes to join the halves are sized for M2 screws.

description.text:
Well, here it is.

This is a multi-purpose carrying case for your collection of Blade Inductrix FPV, FPV Pro and FPV +

I've created files so you can print a version as shown for 2 FPV Pluses, and 4 FPV/FPV Pro's. In addition to a case for either 2 or 4 FPV Pluses or 2 or 4 FPV/FPV Pros.

I think you will be able to sort the versions out by the files names.

It uses the following case from Harbor Freight

https://www.harborfreight.com/20-bin-medium-portable-parts-storage-case-62778.html

or

https://www.harborfreight.com/19-bin-portable-parts-storage-case-93928.html

I think the Harbor Freight cases are pretty much identical. And over time, I think I've ended up with both. The only difference I can tell, is that the inside bins, are just a tad taller in one version than the other. But for this, it makes no difference.

I've designed a few flavors of this for your choosing. You can print only what you need, and then use the extra plastic bins that come included in the Harbo Freight case, to fill up the rest of the space.

For the version shown, which is 2 FPV Plus Cases and 4 FPV/FPV/ Pro cases, print

2 each - V22 FPV Plus Bottom Thin
4each - V22 FPV Bottom Thin
1x - V22 1st, 2nd, 3rd & 4th Insert

Next up, I'm designing an insert for a 4 way charger, and also for the Spektrum Display.

I print this all 4/4/4 and the walls print solid, due to my .4mm nozzle. I'm really pleased with it.

Enjoy.

Oh, if you notice the versions, which have a battery holder, you will find those posted in my other things. I didn't include them here, because you can't close the case lid with batteries in the little FPV holder. But if you want to just carry one around (and not tote the Harbor Freight case, you can print the battery holder version, and then print the lids in my other posts.

description.text:
This model contains a fused segment of the tibia and fibula, as well as the bones of the foot. The bones of the big toe are fused, all other toes are fused together, and the cuneiforms are fused. This was done to reduce the number of printed bones to 8, making a model that is easy to print and study from if you are learning osteo/arthrokinematics of the foot.

In this model the head of the talus does not quite fit into the navicular. I'd love it if someone remixed that problem away.

Someone pointed out in the comments that the files were scaled wrong and that was definitely the case! It should be fixed now.

20%

Notes:

Printed on white Ultimaker PLA.

foot_bones_remix

I used two models to create this remix, using meshmixer. Both original models are superb.

The first model is the right leg long bones by Mooselake (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:157696). I joined the tibia and fibula to create a single mortise joint and cut the model to create a reasonably sized crural piece that can articulate to the talus.

The second model is the foot bones by DrGlassDPM (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:22628). I downloaded the LWO file, converted to STL, and joined several of the 26 bones to generate a simpler model. The sesamoids and phalangeal bones of the big toe are fused, all of the other toes are fused together, and the cuneiforms are fused.

author: jcsalmon

description.text:
Hi,
This is the BreezeBlock fan shroud for the CR-10 Printer. I wanted to design a sleek fan shroud that worked with the 5015 blower, but did not have a bulky profile. It was also important to me that the parts print easily without having to use supports. Since it does not use supports, it does require a bit of extra hardware.

Printer Brand:

Creality

Printer:

CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

30

Notes:

i used 4 walls to make part extra durable
the shroud contains a small piece of built in support in the mouth it snaps out easily
Print 2 of each Part Except the L shaped arms, Print 2 of them.

Install instructions.
1: Remove metal fan cover, or any existing fan shroud so just your hot end assembly is on the mounting plate
2: remove the 40 mm fan from the previous shroud.
3: place the Breezeblock harness over the hotend assembly as show and attach it with 2 m3 6mm(6mm threaded post) screws (if you are using a sensor mount hold it on top of the harness and attach both at same time.
4: Take the harness support arm and fit it clamping over the back corner of the mounting plate and attach it with 2 2 m3 6mm(6mm threaded post)
5: Snap each of the L shaped arm brackets under the hooks and line up the screw hole and fasten with a m3 6mm(6mm threaded post) screw
6: push your 5015 fan exhaust into the opening and use 2 4m x 28mm(28mm post (can be longer)) and 2 nuts to attach the fan, it should be real snug, the tension is what keeps the fan held in tight.
(you can use 4 shorter screws to hold the fan in like i have in my pic, it just does not hold as good as having screws that go all the way thru.
7: place the 40 mm fan inside the shroud, with airflow blowing inwards toward the hotend assembly, and us 4 M3 x 15mm(you can prob get slightly shorter screws to work but around 15 mm is ideal.)to go thru the shroud slots thru the 40mm fan screw holes, and into the holes on the brezeblock harness you can adjust the shroud up and down slightly to get the best flow for your nozzle before snugging the screws all the way.
8:connect the wiring for your fans, and snap the ptfe tube into the guide
9: if using a sensor attach that to mount

description.text:
This is a wall mounted universal spool holder. The design uses two cones that are tightened by a threaded rod to fit most spools. Bearings are used for the cones to achieve very smooth filament feeding. The cone holder is attached to a mount that can be attached to most walls using plastic anchors. The hardware required is relatively inexpensive and can be purchased for about $10 (US).

 I chose this design because I wanted a universal spool holder and something that would not clutter my already small desk. Since my 3D printer is too small to have a frame mounted spool holder and I do not plan on moving my printer anywhere else, I chose to mount it on the wall. The spool I am using is a 1 kg roll of PETG and the mount has no trouble supporting it. The bearings provide smooth feeding and I have not had any issues so far.

PART LIST:
2x Printed Cones
1x Printed Wall Mount
4x Micro Bearings 13mm OD x 4mm ID x 5mm Thick
https://www.ebay.com/itm/Shielded-Micro-Mini-Small-Wheel-Ball-Bearings-624Z-5-pcs-M8P2-/253378889967?hash=item3afe8f08ef
1x Threaded Rod #6-32x6" or M4-0.7x150
2x Matching US or Metric nuts
1x Matching US or Metric Wing Nut
High Strength Loctite or Epoxy
3x plastic anchors with matching screws

ASSEMBLY:
One of the nuts should be glued with epoxy onto one tip of the threaded rod.
The threaded rod should then be passed through the wall mount so that the nut is flush with the mount.
The other nut should be tightened down on the other side the wall mount.
The wall mount can then be mounted onto the wall.
The bearings should be pressed down into place on each side of the cones.
One cone goes in large side first. Then the filament. Then the other cone. Then the wing nut to tighten.
*The wing nut should be tight enough to hold the filament but loose enough to rotate freely. Also, the second cone can go in both ways depending on the diameter and thickness of the spool.

title: customizable filament spool hub for PVC pipe

description.text:
I appreciate rowokii's customizable spool holder, but wanted something that would work better with PVC than a threaded rod. Since I have a wide range of spool diameters I didn't want a lot of wasted space or distance between spools in my dry boxes, so I adapted a piece of rowokii's model and simplified it.

I'll add more photos over time and work on this further if anyone has comments/suggestions.

In OpenSCAD, here's what you can customize:

  • 'diameter' -- this is the diameter of the inner hole of your filament spool; the diameter will also print on the piece itself so you can see at a glance which size you're grabbing if you print extras. Be careful to accurately measure this for a snug fit, and to check your spool to see if you have multiple sizes (both photos above are from the same MakerGeeks spool, one side has a diameter of 52mm, the other was 89mm)

  • 'height' -- how thick you'd like this to be; I don't believe in waste, but don't be too conservative or your spool may wobble. I don't believe you need this to be the entire thickness of your spool, but you can create this however you like.

  • 'rod_d' -- diameter of the rod on which you'll be running your spools. In my case, I'm using 3/4" PVC, which has an outer diameter of about 28mm.

description.text:
This is an imperfect model of the human thoracic vertebrae T1-T12. Each vertebra is printed in two halves and can be superglued together.

It is a work in progress. Several vertebrae don't fit together perfectly, the costal facets are invisible, and the intervertebral foramina are closed down. That said, it is useful for learning osteo/arthrokinematics of thoracic spine movement and it combines with cervical and lumbar/sacral models that are available on Thingiverse to make a really neat, life-sized spinal column model (photo shown; model is hanging in the Richardson Library at DePaul University). I used modeling clay as intervertebral discs.

I would love it if someone fixed the issues listed above and remixed this model.

Creating a spinal column from these files and others

These thoracic vertebrae models were created in Meshmixer from scans of plastic vertebrae from a human skeleton model. Scans were created on a Matter and Form 3D scanner and modified in Meshmixer.

To make the spinal column shown in the photo, I superglued the halves of the vertebrae together and used modeling clay for intervertebral discs.

Cervical vertebrae were from this model by bdario91: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2303910

Lumbar vertebrae and sacrum were from this model by dantana: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:781206

Both of those models print great, and the scale/size of all three models is appropriate to print the entire spinal column from those two models and this one. These thoracic vertebrae are rough by comparison to bdario91 and dantana's cervical and lumbar/sacral models, but they complete the spinal column.

title: Heritage 130P (AWB Onesky) Upper assembly and light shroud

description.text:
**Update in progress due to dovetail shoe failure, ring taken down for now**

To replace the entire upper assembly of the Heritage 130P telescope remixed using bckeck555s ring and focuser plate assembly.

After several iterations and redesigns I am happy to release a complete upper reworking of Synta's Heritage 130P telescope aka Astronomers Without Borders (AWB) Onesky. This is a great little scope that I use as a grab and go, it's a 130mm aperture 650mm focal length f5 Newtonian reflector but it collapses to just 14" long when retracted. Being this is a truss tube design I had an issue with stray light reflecting off the secondary being my usual spot for astronomy is my back yard so I started looking into other mods people had produced to block the light and found several good ides but I had also gotten a 3d printer so "Why not put the two together?" I thought, The result is this. In my search I found bckeck555's various designs for this scope and they were gracious enough to provide me the original models they created to make a few of their designs, full attribution for the upper ring and the focuser mounting plate goes to them, I added the dovetail shoe and the shroud itself while also modifying the ring to have mounting holes and combining the ring, focuser plate and dovetail shoe into a single piece, the down side to that being my current design is to glue a focuser to the plate thus making replacement impossible without reprinting the entire upper ring assembly, but that's for V2. I felt it was important to keep the shroud and ring separate in case the shroud should ever shattered which I haven't experienced yet but have had these separate on the layer seams so I thought replacement should be easy

title: MGN12H Titan Extruder Carriage for Tevo Tarantula w/ BLTouch Mount

description.text:
Update 2018-03-06
Added simple wiring clamp. Future version will include mounting holes for the RJ45 ports.

UPDATE:
Seeing as to how there have already been a few downloads, I've uploaded the top cover and the "short back" version of the main carriage. These should be all you need if you just want to get your Titan up and running. I also included the MGN12H_X_Carriage_Lower.stl from my previous design. This is what your belt attaches to.

If you're looking to use the RJ45 breakouts as in my previous design, you'll have to download the mount separately and that'll work with this carriage.

As I said before, I'm hoping to get some comments or suggestions on the design so that I can make adjustments or modifications.

Features in the current design:

  • Fully covered the stepper motor - This isn't necessary but the cover hides the wiring and the cover also includes the hinge for the part cooling fan.
  • Part cooling fan is a 3010. Same as the one on the E3D V6 fan.
  • Endstop switch mount is still there as in my previous design.
  • BLTouch mount

Features I'm still working on:

  • Bracket to hold the RJ45 breakouts as seen in my previous design.
  • Top cover to hide/route wiring coming from the back of the top cover.
  • The backplane of the main carriage is extruded downwards to hold the RJ45 bracket. If I'm able to find a single dual RJ45 breakout, which were out of stock when I designed my first one, I may decide to mount it on top as in the previous design but facing the back of the printer. If I decide to do that, the backplane will be shortened to match my previous design.

NOTES:

  • M3 screws are used for the part cooling fan and the hinge.
  • The Top cover is held in place by the top 2 screws of the Titan.
  • There is a channel that runs from the fan duct hinge towards the BLTouch. This is so you can run the part cooling fan wire underneath the stepper motor so that it is hidden with the rest of the wires.

Printer Brand:

TEVO

Printer:

Tarantula

Resolution:

0.2mm layer height

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I used PETG for my part because of strength and heat tolerance.

Not much post processing required. As with all my designs, I try to minimize the need for supports so only the main carriage will require supports because it is unavoidable. I tried to design it so it didn't need supports but it would have had to be printed in a couple of pieces and would have to be assembled.

This was designed and rendered in Autodesk Fusion 360.
Models of the Titan Extruder, E3D V6 hotend, BLTouch, and NEMA 17 pancake motor were downloaded from GrabCAD.

Customizable dry box bar mount.

Happy to hear feedback from anyone at any time on improvements.

In OpenSCAD, here's what you can modify:

  • plate_thickness, the thickness of the plate around the lip, etc
  • rod_d, diameter of the rod you're going to use
  • lip_height, how high you want the lip to be (minus the plate thickness)
  • lip_thickness, how many millimeters thick you want the lip to be
  • bolt_width, the millimeter RADIUS of bolts you're going to use to mount this in your dry box (if you're going to use 4mm M4 bolts, set this to 2, for example)

The overall plate size will be about double that of your rod diameter (slightly bigger), and a support piece will be added under the lip to provide extra support to the bottom of the lip.

description.text:
This is an homage to Iron Man's Arc Reactor! I don't claim that it's 100% accurate in any way but I drew inspiration from photos found online.

For this project, you'll need:

-an Adafruit Trinket 5v Controller
-a 24 LED Neopixel Compatible LED ring
-a single Neopixel Compatible LED (I cut mine from an existing neopixel strip)
-various short length M3 self-tapping screws (~5mm)

Remember to print with supports as necessary for the Diffuser and Center ring assembly. The outer ring needs to be glued to the diffuser once you've assembled everything else.

To wire the LEDs to the controller, make sure the LED ring input is wired to the 5v, gnd, and #4 pins on the Trinket. Then wire the single LED to the data, 5v, and gnd outputs of the ring.

The files are available publicly on OnShape under the name "new arc reactor" by Mike Via. Feel free to modify them as necessary...just don't curse me for my dodgy design skills!

You'll have to download and include the Adafruit Neopixel libraries...reference Adafruit's website for more information. I've included the code I modified slightly from the included library below. I've uploaded code to mine that introduces a slow fade effect.

Enjoy!

Arduino Code 

#include 
#define LEDPIN 4 // connect the Data from the strip to this pin on the Arduino
#define NUMBER_PIEXELS 27 // the number of pixels in your LED strip
Adafruit_NeoPixel strip = Adafruit_NeoPixel(NUMBER_PIEXELS, LEDPIN, NEO_GRB + NEO_KHZ800);

int waitTime = 10; 
int minBrightness = 100; // How dim you want the fade to go to (0-255)
int maxBrightness = 200; // How bright you want the fade to go to (0-255)

void setup() {
  strip.begin();
}

void loop() {
  fadeInAndOut(0, 255, 255, waitTime); // Cyan
}

void fadeInAndOut(uint8_t red, uint8_t green, uint8_t blue, uint8_t wait) {

  for(uint8_t b=minBrightness; b  minBrightness; b--) {
     for(uint8_t i=0; i < strip.numPixels(); i++) {
        strip.setPixelColor(i, red*b/255, green*b/255, blue*b/255);
     }
     strip.show();
     delay(wait);
  };
};

description.text: A stand for the wonderful TS100 soldering iron, with a place for a copper wire tip cleaner, a spool of solder and a small tray for tweezers and a flux pen.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Any

Infill:

10%

Notes:

There shouldn't be any need for supports or a raft if your printer is dialed in well and you're not printing in ABS :)

Parts needed
  • 1x Base print
  • 2x Axle print
  • Small piece of copper sheet to support the hot end of the iron (optional, since the part we need to support doesn't really get that hot, but you'll need to redesign the support column)
  • 2x Ball bearing - 13mm OD, 4mm ID, 5mm Depth (optional, but you'll need to modify the axle parts)
  • 2x Cylinder magnet - 2mm Height, 12mm Diameter (optional)
  • 2 small pieces of PTFE Bowden tube (optional)
Rough drawing of the copper sheet cutout before bending Making the copper support

Cut out a shape similar to the one in the image above out of the copper sheet. Bend along the dashed lines to wrap around the short support post. It will need to be adjusted for fit with both the base and the soldering iron itself, bend and cut until you have something good.

"Assembly"
  • Put the two axle halves back-to-back and push the bearing on the ends. This should hold the axle together, no need for glue.
  • Place a solder roll on the axle and the axle onto its two supports.
  • Put two pieces of the PTFE Bowden tube into the solder guide. If you want, make one into a friction clamp, to keep the end of the solder wire in place. Pull the solder through the guide.
  • Place the copper support piece (from the previous step) onto its post
  • Place the two magnets into their holes under where the tip cleaner goes. They should be a friction fit, but you can also glue them in. Place the tip cleaner on the magnets.
  • Place your TS100 in your new soldering stand
Bonus step: Cable extension

This has little to do with the stand itself, but in the photos, you can see I use wire extension from the laptop power brick that I use with my TS100. The extension is specifically made from silicone-insulated stranded wire, which makes it super soft and comfortable to work with. It never gets in the way and even if it does, the insulation can't be harmed by the heat of the iron.

I especially recommend this if your PSU has a right angle connector because having that right at the iron is PITA.

Interlocking hexes for building 3D landscapes for use in board games such as Battletech.

Shapes

There are a variety of shapes included, but each is based on a hex size of 2 inches at the base and a height of 6 mm. The following shapes are included:

Single Hex

Good for foothills. The zero height hexes, incidentally, are mostly good for color like water, grass, fire/lava, or desert.

  • Height 0 - good for ground cover like trees or water (Hex-1x1-H0.stl)
  • Height 1(Hex-1x1-H1.stl)
  • Height 2 (Hex-1x1-H2.stl)

Line

Good for mountain ranges.

  • Height 1 (HexLine-4x1-H1.stl)
  • Height 4 (HexLine-4x1-H4.stl)

Triangle

Good for elevating a large area or conversely creating a depressed area for water or a canyon

  • 2X2 Height 1 (HexTriangle-2x2-H1.stl)
  • 3X3 Height 1 (HexTriangle-3x3-H1.stl)
  • 3X3 Height 3 (HexTriangle-3x3-H3.stl)
  • 4X4 Height 1 (HexTriangle-4x4-H1.stl)
  • 4X4 Height 2 (HexTriangle-4x4-H2.stl)
  • 4X4 Height 4 (HexTriangle-4x4-H4.stl)

Water

This is a two part piece, a flat bottom part (Base), and an outside ridge (Rim) that simulates where the top of the water is, yet allow mechs to sit down in the water to provide a more realistic line of sight.

  • 4X1 Line Base (HexWater-4x1-H0.stl)
  • 4X1 Line Rim (HexWater-4x1-H1.stl)
  • 4X2 Thick Line Base (HexWater-4x2-H0.stl)
  • 4X2 Thick Line Rim (HexWater-4x2-H1.stl)

Note: The bridge shown in the pictures is a separate part (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2814838).

Printing

As far as printing I would recommend a brim for better platform adhesion, and since quality probably isn't as important as speed I'd go with the largest layer height you can do. In my case I went with .3 mm layer height.

I made all walls .8mm to optimize the print for my .4mm extruder nozzle so that it only needs two passes. Given all that with a speed of 60mm/s it took 15 minutes for a single hex, ~2.75 hours for HexTriangle-4x4-H1.stl and ~5 hours for the really large print: HexTriangle-4x4-H4.stl.
I had to print one ring at a time because the 2 stl files would separate if I tried to fill the plate.

title: QR Code magnet - use for guest wifi access - parametric / openscad

description.text:
go to https://ridercz.github.io/OpenSCAD-QR/ and enter your QR code text, and it will generate the data for you. copy only the qr_data array into the scad file.

for guest wifi, use "WIFI:T:WPA;S:<SSID_HERE>;P:<PASSWORD_HERE>;;" without the quotes, e.g. WIFI:T:WPA;S:Get off my LAN;P:guest password;;

I would also recommend changing the magnet size variables, and testing it with your magnets before printing. use the magnet_test() module for this.

I printed mine dual extrusion, there is a module for each of the dual extrusion parts.

There is also a module for single extrusion, where you would pause after the base 3mm is printed in white, change filament to black, then resume and print the last couple layers for the black part of the QR code.

title: Marble ball release mechanism cylinder version

description.text:
Danger of finger injury
It is recommended to glue tube as least longer than a finger to each entrance of the device to prevent accidents with fingers being poked into the device while in operation, a nasty finger injury could result without such safety guards.

Marble release mechanism 2

Revisit of marble release problem, my previous "beam engine" style device that was not reliable enough at delivering a single ball every time.
This is a very reliable mechanism allowing only one 21mm diameter ball to drop at a time, it does not fail!

Instructions:

Attach a SG90 micro servo. Use M2.5 nut and bolt to mount the servo to the mounting points. See photographs for guide.

Mount the round hub gear to the servo horn, cutting off the tips so they do not foul the meshing of the gear teeth.

The cylinder rotates through 120 degrees to release the ball from a 30 degree feed tube (25mm electrical conduit) to a vertical drop out the bottom. 25mm electrical conduit should friction fit into the holes.

Use the washer superglued to the shaft (only) to keep the cylinder in place. It should be glued hard against the face so there is no lateral movement, or the gears my loose mesh. The open cone side of the washer should be placed against the face as it has less surface area (less friction) and also the gap between shaft and washer should help prevent the super glue getting onto the face and gluing the shaft it in position. Keep moving the shaft while drying to ensure it does not get stuck.

The square of the other gear cog should push onto the cylinder with a firm friction fit. Glue if required for extra security.

If a clean print has been made, then the cylinder should move very smoothly and freely in its position before the motor is attached.

Before screwing on the servo horn, thus meshing the gears, find the mid position of the servo and set this to be the mid position of the cylinder movement, so that when manually moving the servo it covers the range needed to release the ball.

Enjoy and do please comment and post photos if you make this, as it motivates me to post more!
https://youtu.be/5PLN1OL_mF0
https://youtu.be/kqvsuGK7beo
https://youtu.be/cNvKvMjKVTQ
https://youtu.be/tcLlVTGSCCc

UPDATED 2018-03-10
Changed spur gears to 40 from 48 tooth for ease of printing.

title: Raspberry Pi & LiFePO4 UPS + Fan Case

description.text:
I used a Raspberry Pi 3 to make a "Pi-Hole" (https://pi-hole.net/) local caching DNS server, and ad and tracker blocker. Being a full-time part of my network, I wanted reliability. The thing about Raspberry Pi's is that if power is interrupted you can sometimes have the SD card get corrupted and require re-imaging. Not hard but the network gets interrupted.

I added a smart UPS from LiFe PO4wered (https://lifepo4wered.com/lifepo4wered-pi3.html) to keep from corrupting the SD card but now it wouldn't fit any of the other 3D-printable cases. And that's where this comes in. That LiFePO4 UPS is very cool. Best to let their features page explain it, but it's amazingly powerful both in battery and configurability. The hole in the top of the case is to get to the touch pad power button.

It's drawn from the ground up but I followed the design of Baudler ArtDesign. This case is taller since I didn't cut out the the USB and network connectors, and it needed to clear the LiFePO4 battery and holder. I put some ducting in to help with the air flow over the chip heatsinks and recessed the fan down into the case for a cleaner design.

The fan is just a 30mm x 30mm x 8mm Pi-Fan I got at Amazon and it's a friction fit into the recess. The fan really makes a difference in chip temperatures. It was running 115F with no fan and no case as reported by the Pi-Hole software, but with the fan in this case, the temperature comes in at 96F while running the 5 volt fan off 3.3 volts since the LiFePO4 UPS covers the 5 volt terminals. I might modify things to get 5 volts for the fan, but that's another story. It's still just shy of a 20F drop in operating temperature.

title: ePIc Kinect ( Raspberry Pi 2 and 3 case)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
ePIc Kinect has a universal mounting system running down all 4 sides of it. It was designed so I could easy just slide different mounts on to the case in a bunch of different configurations. I hope you all enjoy it.

I have added a bunch of mounts that I have tested and all seem to work. If you have something you would like to use as a mount and cant design it yourself send me a message and I will look into adding it to the collection below. If you do Design it yourself please feel free to post it on thingiverse and link this model so we can find them easily. I will add links as well to other peoples mounts.

A few notes on the case options
One unit has an option to mount a 40mm fan inside the other does not. I thought it was nice to have a fan mount but realized it didn't look as clean with it for those that don't need a fan. It also has a cam port open and the pin cover can be snapped off if you need access to them.

I didn't use any supports when I printed.

I do NOT orientate all the parts correctly when I upload them so you will need to orientate them correctly in order to print with no supports.

You have to mount the pi first and then snap in the port cover. Put the edge in with the audio port first then snap the cover in place on the power side of the cover. There are tiny tabs on the port cover so it doesnt take much to hold it in place.

4 screws 3mm x 8mm should help square the pi up in the case through the bottom feet but they are not a requirement as the port cover and nose cover lock the pi in place.

The mounting brackets have one hole smaller than the other on purpose so you can thread them to whatever screws you like. 8-32 will be the easiest to thread to.

If you like it, please dont hesitate to tip a couple bucks:) I do appreciate it and as much as I like sharing these they do take time to create...

As with most of my designs I only allow personal use only.. If you want to make money on my designs let me know and we can work out something. I have been modifying the designs per cleint with a unique model so we can keep track of them.

If you cant get it to print yourself you can order one from me here.

description.text:
This is a mount and switch block to keep the head of an airbrush compressor cool. It uses a fan salvaged from an old computer powered by a 12volt DC "wall wart" transformer. The switch is of the generic type found at any hardware store.

It is quite effective at keeping the head cool as you can see on this video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PHM2jFTXwAc&t=2s

The cooler head will help prevent water from condensing inside the line and possibly extend the life of your compressor. Especially the cheap eBay compressors.

I printed this on my Makerbot Mini. The base was printed with 3 shells and 50% fill.

A screw goes down through the top next to the switch and a nut secures the bottom wire cover (See the upside down photo). The head of the screw is epoxied in place and the "FAN" plate is glued ontop to hide it. One photo shows the switch mounted with the screw sticking out. Another photo shows the inside of the wire cover to show a view of the wire strain relief arrangement.

The power wire goes through the notch on the end of the wire cover. The fan wires enter through the side notch.

It attaches and detaches easily from the compressor as shown in the video. The tabs that fit into the compressor fins are made a bit thick so to fit many compressor models. You will need to file / sand them to fit your model. They should fit snug between the head fins but not wedged tight.

title: Extensible Arithmetic Spinner, Math Spinner, Math Wand, Snap Spinner

description.text:
Arithmetic Spinner, Math Spinner, Math Wand, Snap Spinner, Extensible

The math spinner does not teach. However, it might motivate children to think about mathematics and ask questions such as “What does that mod thing do?” or “Is it okay if I say 5 + 3 > -20?” It could be used as a random problem poser.

Children like problems that are tangible. Using snapping structures, I have figured out a way to make an extensible arithmetic spinner or math wand. There are four types of rings, each of which is 25mm in diameter at the interior circle and 35mm at the outside and 10mm wide:

  1. Digits (0-9),
  2. Arithmetic operators( +, -, ×, ÷, mod). Modular arithmetic is an important idea. It simply means keeping the remainder. For example, 15 mod 7 = 1 .
  3. Relational operators (=, ≠, <, ≤, >, ≥)
  4. Signs (+, -, blank/unsigned)
  5. Cap 1, optional.
  6. Cap 2, optional.

One can print multiple sets, mix and match, and create very long number sentences such as ### × ## = ##### or ## × # + # = ###. The end caps are optional.

Please be very careful not to hurt fingers when snapping rings together. Gloves are recommended. To remove a ring after assembly, please use a flat-end screw driver and slowly pry it off. Have fun and help kids do some math!

title: FT-5 Dual E3D V6 Bowden Gantry

description.text:
Here's my take on a dual extruders for my FolgerTech FT-5. The Gantry itself is fairly basic. Two E3D V6 heat sink mounts 25mm apart, recessed and rounded posts for the GT2 belt, sunken nut captures all-around. The cooling fan attachment was a bit of work. It takes two standard 40mm fans and has fairly effective part cooler vents as well. I also modelled a 'hat' that fits on top for securing the cabling. I don't use a cable chain however the screw holes should match.

Some notes:
Head alignment can be a huge pain. The gantry has the heat sinks exactly 25mm apart on the X axis and no delta on the Y however depending on the exact shapes of your heatsinks (eg: two different clones or originals) and how you torqued the screws can throw it off by a mm or two. I was at 26x.3 offsets for my test prints.

Z alignment can be even more tricky. I originally shimmed each bolt using washers but that was not precise enough. Then pieces of card but that was a huge pain. What I found worked best was to put two layers of felt between the gantry and the slider then torque them down all the way. Slightly loosen the lower under until they line up.

I ended up using two different clones and two different extruders (a Titan and a direct) so had to tweak and tune a LOT to even get passable prints. That wasn't due to the gantry though. Everything seemed solid and it was Cura and Simplify 3D that drove me crazy.

I'm moving dual extrusion to my i3 and keeping the FT-5 as a high-speed, high-temp workhorse. Don't expect many more improvements to this but I'm happy to provide the steps if someone wanted to make some tweaks.

I top mounted the filament spools and motors. Here is the thing for the motor mounts: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1357814. I created extra tall and extra solid arms to hold the spools on a 5/16 threaded rod. Also have some washers for 5/16 nuts as well.

description.text:
I accidentally busted the temperature (climate control) knob on the Toyota Highlander. I found that the interior mount for the knob was poorly-designed and had easily snapped off ... and there was no way to fix it! Toyota said they couldn't replace just that part, but could replace the whole system for >$1000!

I simply made a new, stronger version and printed it. It attaches to the grey knob in the same way as the original, but is much more solid. Uses the little metal piece to turn the post and fits snugly.

This is a great way to save a LOT of money on something so silly. Let me know if you need me to print it for you, it'd cost $9 shipped in the US.

Attach the printed part on the post for your knob (after disassembling the climate control unit a bit). Put the climate control unit back together, and reinstall to dash. Then, re-attach knob - it will click in to the printed part.

description.text:
Since my ham-handed slicer tends to lay on the supports pretty thick, I modified this
design to print treads separately without support. I also never liked the way the
various Tigers printed the rear, so I stripped it off so it can be printed detail up.
Printed this way, the rear is much cleaner and takes paint and washes much better.

The hulls included will need support due to the overhang for the tread. As a further
experiment, I also broke the hull down to print in two pieces so no support is needed;
that's in the "2 piece" zip file.

I still suggest support for the rear plate as it will help the tailpipes print. After removing the support, I reinforced the tailpipe with thin super glue to make them a little sturdier. Also use support for the barrel and glue a piece of filament in the hole to attach it to the hull. Note the barrels can be drilled if you have a pin vise, it looks great!

I included an open hatch hull and a tiny printible hatch for commander versions. The
commander in the original doesn't print for me so I used a figure I had laying around.

title: Arduino Starter Kit: Electronic Components Divider

description.text:
The Arduino Starter Kit is a good tool to introduce mechatronics to beginners. The package itself is neatly divvied up in cardboard boxes. However, the inside of the Electronic Components box may seem somewhat of a disorganization in the pieces all bundled in a bag. This can be used to organize the inside of that box into separate categories: the piezo, the LEDs, the pots/transistors/switches, and the other loose electronics with all the jumpers resting atop topped with a simple layer to cover everything (with a hole for easy take-out). It fits and slides easily into the Electronic Components box without having to discard any cardboard material.

A small yet sturdy travel SD card holder with a key! You can print this so that your sd cards don't get ruined in your pocket and bag plus the larger size means its easy to find in a bag full of stuff. I use this when carrying an SD card too and from school or if I'm going on a trip where I need an Sd card.

The assembly is really straightforward just screw the locking screw into the box (you don't have to unscrew it all the way to open it) and slide in the actual Sd holder then screw it in the rest of the way and lock the SD card in place.

This "Designer" is for creating DIN rail holders. So far the features are:

  • Creates a holder with a circular hole
  • The size of the top and bottom can be independently customized
  • Optional removal of mid-section to save material
  • Optional finger-pull to release the clip
  • A customized chamfer radius can be added to the top of the hole
  • The depth of the clip (front to back) can be customized
  • Some of the other feature sizes can be customized under Advanced parameters

To design your own thing

  1. Download both the .scad and .json files.
  2. Install the Development version of OpenSCAD (http://www.openscad.org/downloads.html#snapshots)
  3. Enable the Customizer according to https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/OpenSCAD_User_Manual/WIP#Customizer
  4. Open the .scad file
  5. Pick your preset or set your customizations
  6. Render
  7. Export as an STL file

Want a feature added? Let me know.

title: Coleman Pop Up Camper Door Latch Handle

description.text:
This is the handle portion of the door latch used on many different camper trailers and RVs over the years. On my camper the latch worked fine but the handle was broken, so I decided it would be good modeling practice for me to create a new one. For the entire latch assembly, the part number is 4742-9671, (https://colemanpopupparts.com/products/screen-door-latch) and can be purchased for around 12 or 13 dollars. But why buy what you can spend a lot more time making.

I have not tried fitting it on the door yet. The studs that accept the mounting screws may need to be reduced in diameter.

The part should be printed on end, for the most strength at the handle. You will need to use supports.

0.2 mm layers, 3 shells, 3 top and bottom layers, 15-25% infill I think would work fine.
Print a few and keep them in the camper for replacement.

title: XBOX ONE Thumb Stick Controller Extension Ver2 BASE and CAP

description.text:
I wanted to create a more versatile Thumb stick with different Cap designs and the ability of using softer materials. These new thumb sticks give you the user the most options for length, Cap style and material, and color scheme.

Length dimension is the total height change you get with a 4.4mm thick cap added on.

You will need to print a Base of the length you prefer and then print a Cap from here or design your own. Then just glue them together.

The Thumb Sticks just press on your controller and have a very firm grip. I have not had one come off during gaming yet.

I also did include a ZIP file with all the Bases without the support structure.

CAP DESIGN:
If you create your own cap to use with one of the bases, added it as a remix so other users can find it and try it out.

Thanks:
Thanks to "3dprinteraneta8" who did a remix of my first design and got me thinking on how to improve it...

PLEASE:
If you make one of these and use it come back and give it a "LIKE" and show your make and tell us about it and the materials you used.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.100 - .200

Infill:

100%

Notes:

THIS is not a "I'm going to make that my first print!". You want your printer tuned in to be able to bridge some and printing well to do these.

BASE PRINTING:
I printed these in PLA+ and PETG and both work really well (great layer bonding). Highly recommend you print these at a slow speed (PETG at 1500mm/min is what I used). It was designed and intended to be printed with a .4mm nozzle and with a .2mm layer thickness for the bases.

You can print these without a raft but failure rate is much higher. I've tried lots of approaches to printing this and using a raft works almost every time. I included a support with a .4mm tall grooved top and a .2mm gap from the part. I just pull it off with a needle nose pliers easily.

CAP PRINTING:
The caps can be printed at a .2mm layer also but they look best at a .1mm layer. You do not need a raft or any supports for these. Use a softer material to customize your feel.

author: cairoringo

print_settings.Notes:: I print these in ABS for flexibility and durability.

description.text:
A machine that my partner needs to use for work comes with really terrible cables that fail all the time due to a lack of adequate strain relief. I tried several methods to reinforce them for her, and while productive, none of them worked super well. So I tried something else and was really pleased with the result.

There's some built-in support material (brim?) on the bottom that you need to remove. Without it I was unable to get good yield. It's 0.15mm and therefore 1 layer thick with the settings that I used. It can be trivially broken off with tweezers.

Most other strain relief designs that I've found on Thingiverse are fully round and printed with the central axis vertical on the plate. This one is rectangular to provide a build surface, allowing it to be printed with the central axis in XY. Doing that eliminates the need to have support material inside the coils, substantially reducing post-print manual cleanup.

I wouldn't be surprised if it's possible to print it without the brim, but with a stickier build plate. I'll give that a shot (e.g., with glue stick) and if it works out OK, will post a model without the brim.

title: Tronxy E3D V6 Holder with part cooling mount

description.text:
I see alot of E3D V6 adapters for Tronxy but none of them had a part cooling fan. So I made one using Catia. I made it for my chinese replica V6. I designed 3 versions of it and this one has been my workhorse. I only release it now because I'm confident that it'll work for you if proprely mounted. The one on my printer right now has over 200hrs of printing and there's no sign of heat distorsion whatsoever.

The mount requires 4XM3 nuts and screws for the clamp and the fan. I highly suggest adding spacers.
My first version had slots to drop in the nuts and screw but the PLA kept cracking with the pressure. So this version you have to press in two nuts. for the back (see picture).
The mounting the holes are for M4 screws of the radial fan, but I suggest using some M3 to give you wiggle room.
I've done multiple iterations of the duct and the one present is the one I found the most effective. Knowing that I worked with a CAD of the full assembly I've allowed myself only a 1mm gap in the Z axis between the nozzle tip and the duct (Subject to the hotend you have if a replica.) It simply is press fitted in the fan, don't need to glue it.

My stock fan had a broken wire so I replaced it with a blower to have better cooling and drilled some holes in the plastic clip. I used the E3D V6 Blower Fan adapter by matt448 for that purpose (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1600018).

WARNING:
I have to warn that my adapter shifts forward the hot end by about 5mm forward (see picture). So for that purpose I've designed a endstop bracket du to the lack of time I have because of school. By experience you might have to trim some tensionners if you want the full 150mm in th Y axis. So far this didn't cause me anyproblems.

I used an exact CAD model of a E3D V6 with a tigh fit tolerances. But you might need to file a little bit to be able to insert it.

FUTURE CONSIDERATIONS:
-Shift the hotend backward to eliminate the 5mm shift.
-I might want to add a part to attach a cable chain for my next update.
-Move the radial fan bracket higher to give more flexibility for the cooling duct.
-Make a version for a normal fan instead of a blower fan. Blower fans a good for high air volume and normal radial fans can build up pressure better. So the cooling duct could be both sides.

Printer:

Tronxy X1

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20

Notes:

I made it using 1mm walls (all sides) so it can withstand the screws.
My bed is a piece of glass and I can control well my warping. I didn't use a raft, but it can be usefull for some.
I made it with PLA since I print almost only that with my printer, but a higher temp plastic could be nice if you need to print at higher temps.

You need to press fit two M3 nuts in the back of the mount to attach the clamp.

You might need to file the clamp area, some printers might not have the precision to do it within the design tolerances.

description.text:
Some say, 12 cards are not enough.
Thats the reason why i've created a new SD-Rotor for 25 cards. It works like my first version:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2803750

The 12 and 25 card holder are stackable with some rubber bumpers.

New: rotor and stator are aligned for printing (no need to turn upside down)

The stator has an integrated support for the center hole. After printing, you can push the support out through the screwhole. (There is a gap between support and body of 0.2 mm)

You need a screw M6x30 an M6 washer and an M6 Locknut.

The pointer is to show you where the lifting cam stays.

Press the pointer on the nut after tighten.
Use the " pointer " when the lifting cam comes to rest on the edge of the nut.
Use the "pointer flat" when the lifting cam comes to rest on the surface of the nut.

I hope someone understands this. ;-)

description.text:
I won't call this thing a work in progress because it functions as is, but you should note that the picture frame glass can very between manufacturers, so please take note that this frame should fit standard picture frame glass (dollar store) that measures smaller than 260 x 214 mm.

The lighted portion of the box uses standard 5050 SMD light 300 LED per 5m light strips and needs to be soldered or attached within the bottom portion of the box.

I have included both insert types for the bottom portion of the box the larger insert allows the frame to stand upright.

I designed this in tinkercad so unfortunately I do not have any build files for it but if you do want to modify the STL's feel free to do so. The two side pillars attach to the base with CA glue or other epoxy. I have made recessed tabs for each pillar so they will only slide into their respective sides when assembled with CA glue. The top of the base slides on over the tabs on each pillar so you can switch between glass etchings if you want to.

I have designed all fitted parts to have at least a 0.30 mm tolerance, so a strong first layer and/or minor over extrusion should not interfere with fit. You may want to print the pillars with support for the overhang on the top tabs, they will sit 90 degrees to the build plate other wise the spot for the glass will sit 90 degrees and need support.

The bottom of the frame is designed for smaller LED receivers you can find on eBay, gearbest or banggood. If you need more information on assembly and parts you can see a timelapse of the wiring and bottom frame here. https://youtu.be/6OgNLKKodbQ

There are multiple STLs included here that are grouped together and independent pieces, the grouped files may need a large printer, I used the CR-10 but you can print pieces independently.

title: JGAurora Z603S Infrared Autobed Level Modification
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
JG Aurora Z603S Infrared sensor upgrade

https://youtu.be/L8FqyaKwRao

This only works for the later GREEN motherboard.

WARNING WARNING

MAKE SURE YOU DOUBLE CHECK YOUR CONNECTIONS
POSITIVE to POSITIVE
NEGATIVE to NEGATIVE
SIGNAL to SIGNAL

I soldered an extra 3 pin socket to my green motherboard (PIN 18). This is where the IR sensor is plugged in. Please check the image for the correct connection. The original opto Z min endstop has been disabled in the firmware as I intend to use it as a filament sensor input in the future. You can if you wish plug your new IR sensor into the Z min to save soldering anything. If you do this then you will need to change the allocated #define Z_MIN_PIN in the PINS_Z603s sketch back to pin 19.

WARNING WARNING

Description
Autobed level addition to the JG Aurora Z603S 3D printer.

Items you will require
Infrared sensor - https://miscsolutions.wordpress.com/mini-height-sensor-board/
3 wire servo extension lead (2 x 1m in length)

Files included
Mount STL
Cover
New X endstop trigger
Firmware 1.1.8 Marlin

To do this modification you will need to update the main board's firmware. You will need to update using the Arduino IDE software.
There are plenty of youtube videos showing you how to do this, just search for update marlin via arduino ide.

You will need to open your machine up and feed the 3 wire connector around the machine. The sensor uses a new 3 pin connector which I soldered too on the main board. If you do not want to do this then you can alter the firmware to use the Z minimum endstop connector. See above for changing to the pins info in the firmware required.

The current z endstop needs to be removed. Just unscrew it from the side frame and hide it below. You can always go back then if needed.

I've already configured the firmware to use this sensor, so you will only need to flash it. I have enabled the eeprom on the board, so you can save
bed levels.. but I would level at the start of every print just to be safe.

To level, you will need to add some gcode lines to your start gcode script. There is normally a tab / section in your software.. the lines you need to add are,

M851 Z-3.1 ; Z Offset
M500 ; Save to Eeprom
G28 ; Home
G29 ; Level bed
etc...

The Z offset can be set above. Z-1.0 = 1mm.. so if you want to lower the head then you would do..
M851 Z-1.2 ; Z Offset
This would then be 0.2mm closer than before.

Let me know how you get on.. Any questions please ask away and don't forget to like this :-)

I would also recommend adding the following to your gcode start / stop script in your preferred printing program.

START SCRIPT
M851 Z-3.1 ; Z Offset <--- NOTE you will need to change this value
M500 ; Save to Eeprom
G28 ; home all axes
G29 ; Level bed
G1 X10 Y10 F9000 ; get ready to prime
G1 Z0.3 F6000
G92 E0 ; reset extrusion distance
G1 X240 Y10 E24 F2000
G1 X250 Y10 F180
G1 X260 Y10 F5000

END GCODE
G1 X0 Y180 F3000 ; Move bed / head
G1 Z170 F3000 ; Move bed / head
M106 S0 ; turn off cooling fan
M104 S0 ; turn off extruder
M140 S0 ; turn off bed
M84 ; disable motors

Then disable SKIRT or BRIM as you wont need it anymore.

This is a LME8UU case tested in metallic linear bearings.

Tevo tarantula Y axis upgrade:

This alows you to use the stock acrilic base to upgrade to dual Y rods.

You also will need 2 450x8mm rods and front and back rod holders. You can use whatever but just be sure that has the correct height. The acrilic base MUST be highter than the 4020 aluminium center profile. This design level up the acrilc base 8 mm from the center of the rods. So i recommend you to use front and back holders with a 34 mm or more height to have at least 2mm clearence between the acrilic base and 4020 profile. I am using a 42 mm height of my own.

Thing you have to print:
4 lm8uu case

Setup:
There is no need to sand anything there is a perfect fit. Holes are for M3 so are the nuts.
First of all, download or design the front and back mount you are going to use.
Mesure distances between rods.
Then do a drilling template (2D printer).
Start using a small drill like 1,5mm or 2mm.
In order to be very accurate in the assembly you should drill LME8UU case 4mm holes in the M3 holes, this will alow you to correct the error.
Assemble all the 4 LME8UU case to the acrilic base but just tight a little.
With the base upside down insert the rods and mesure the distances with a caliper.
Correct the distance error and tighten it. Check if the rods can run smooth before assemble in the printer.
Precision 0.1mm

title: 28mm Bar Stool and Chair Gluing Jig

description.text:
First published model warning

I printed a bunch of the Curufin bar stools and chairs and I wanted a way to quickly and consistently glue them together. I made a jig in OnShape.

I may make jigs for Curufin's other models.

Usage

I find it's best to put a couple of bar stool tops in the jig with the bottom facing up. Then apply a drop of CA (superglue) on a couple of bar stool bottoms. Bring the parts together, press toward the back of the jig and or press it down on your work surface.

For the chairs it's pretty much the same. Just check the fit of the chair back in the cutout at the bottom before you try to glue anything. I have a bit of a problem with elephant's foot on my printer so I had to shave just a bit off the sides to make the chairs fit well.

Customizing

I used imported the original chair models into OnShape and used those to design the part. I adjusted the clearances to the chairs I have printed. If my model does not fit your prints well, you could try:

  1. Adjusting the x/y scale in your slicer by a few percent to get a bit more or less clearance.
  2. Customize it in OnShape You can find it here (you will have to have an OnShape account to customize it.) I used variables in the design, you will find them in the "Features" window directly under the planes.
    • # xy_clearance - clearance around the model in the x/y directions, default: 0.4mm. I found that I need much less z clearance than x/y so I split them up.
    • # z_clearance - clearance around the model in the z direction, default: #xy_clearnace/4
    • # count - the number of jigs in the model, default: 2. I planned on printing 4 or 6 wide but after printing it 2 wide to test I found that 2 was plenty enough stressful to use. Superglue is fast!!!
  3. I would be glad to try to help out. Please try to contact me through Thingiverse but be patient. I'm not sure how notifications work and how quickly I'd get them.

description.text:
This spacer is designed to allow a Winstar WEH001602C to be fitted in E-Mu's Proteus range of sound modules (i.e. Proteus 1, 2, 3, Procussion - not the later 2000 range).

NB: replacement of the display in this range is difficult, since it requires desoldering of a 7x2 pin 0.1" DIL header.

I wanted longer pins than on the original to provide the depth, so I removed the header from the panel PCB rather than trying to solder the OLED onto the existing header. Removal of that header is a difficult soldering job, and not without risk to the panel PCB. Undertake at your own risk!

description.text:
Need a hanger for the wall?  
Easy to make your own version as the OpenSCAD file is optimized for Customizer.  
In Customizer your can manipulate size, arc angel, geometry and holes.  
The cola cans and the chair is around 10 kg total and is an example of how much weight just a small hanger in PLA can hold.  
Good luck.

I designed a tabletop bowling game that you can make in a Fablab using a 3D printer and a laser cutter.

I used the pin design from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:385221
And the ball design from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2077303
I scaled down those designs and cut the bottom of the pin in the file, so that is is more stable.

For the build, I laser cut 3mm plywood onto the Trotex Speedy 100 laser cutter.

When printing the pins, set filling to 100%, while when printing the ball, print it the lightest possible. Otherwise the game is too easy.

I found out that the best ball to play bowling with was a cork babyfoot (aka foosball) ball.

I also screw in some screws under the pins so that it would fit nicely into the lane, and speed up the process of resetting the game.

My friend broke a cup holder in his Škoda Fabia (1st gen) so I made him a replacement. Improved. :o)

I printed this from CFJet (PETG with carbon), however regular PETG or even ABS also work. Few small supports are necessary (but only from buildplate). After the print I would recommend a bit sanding or even re-drilling the parts (especially knobs) to ensure everything have correct dimensions and is relatively smooth.

It was difficult and complex design and it is not super easy to print correctly either. There is probably not many Škoda Fabia 1st gen users but let me know if you any need help or more information. Anyway it was very time-consuming design so feel free to tip me when you use this model. :o)

title: vesa mount for drowing tablet Xp-pen artist 15.6
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Supporto con attacco vesa per pannello interattivo Xp-pen artist 15.6, indispensabile se si vuole montare il drowing tablet su un braccetto per monitor.

le parti da stampare sono:

  • Cover X4 pezzi (2 standard e 2 mirror)
  • tappi cover X4 pezzi (2 standard e 2 mirror)
  • vesa2 X1
  • Pomelli dado M4 X4 pezzi

Parti extra

  • Viti M4x40 testa esagonale X4 pezzi
  • Dadi M4 X4pezzi
  • Viti M3x4 X8 pezzi

Montaggio:
-1 Unire le quattro parti della cover insieme incollando i vari lati, aiutandosi con del nastro adesivo
-2 passare le viti attraverso i quattro fori presenti sul supporto "vesa2", assicurandosi che la testa della vite entri nel rispettivo alloggio
-3 incollare il supporto "vesa2" sulla "Cover", assicurandosi di incollare il supporto vesa con le viti sporgenti dalla parte opposta rispetto gli incastri del tablet
-4 posizionare il tablet
-5 Avvitare i "tappi cover" su i relativi incastri
-6 agganciare il tablet sul braccetto

Mounting:
-1 Combine the four parts of the cover together gluing the various sides, using adhesive tape
-2 pass the screws through the four holes on the "vesa2" support, making sure that the screw head enters the respective housing
-3 glue the "vesa2" support on the "Cover", making sure to glue the vesa support with the screws protruding from the opposite side of the tablet joints
-4 place the tablet
-5 Screw the "cover caps" on the relative joints
-6 hook the tablet on the arm

The Idea is that the center can be hold down by hand and the rules can turn around it. In the holes you can stick a ballpoint of pencil. The big holes (2mm) on the red ruler are 10mm apart from each other. The small holes (1mm) are 1mm from each other. The blue ruler has only 2mm holes that are 5mm from each other.
The Centre has a scale divided in 10° segments but also in 0, 22.5, 45, 65.5, 90 etc. With this scale it’s possible to make quarter circles, for instance...
In the center you can fit a 3mm drill, rod or pointy object that can be fixed with an M3x10mm bolt and nut.
